    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>
I previously used my secondary Facebook account as a blog, but soon I felt need for another platform.
I wanted to open my posting with my editor (emacs, org-mode) and update with my VCS (git).
Simple static web site looked fine for me, as <a href="https://github.com/discourse/discourse">Discourse</a> or <a href="https://disqus.com/">Disqus</a> seems to provide satisfiable commenting feature.
I&#8217;ve looked through some examples below.
</p>


<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a href="http://orgmode.org/worg/org-web.html">org web sites</a>
</li>
<li><a href="http://orgmode.org/worg/org-blog-wiki.html">org blogging tools</a>
</li>
<li><a href="https://github.com/joshuaeckroth/cse3521-website">cse3521-website</a>
</li>
</ul>


<p>
As a total newbie on web front-end programming, org-mode, elisp, and blogging, I
</p>


<ul class="org-ul">
<li>myself doesn&#8217;t know exactly which feature I want.
</li>
<li>am hard to deal with problems when I stuck.
</li>
</ul>


<p>
Therefore, large and active community was especially important factor for me.
</p>




<div id="outline-container-sec-1" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="sec-1">Blogging tool</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-1">
</div><div id="outline-container-sec-1-1" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-1-1"><a href="http://renard.github.io/o-blog-v2/">o-blog</a></h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-1-1">
<p>
stuck with this issue : <a href="https://github.com/renard/o-blog/issues/116#issuecomment-59183307">https://github.com/renard/o-blog/issues/116#issuecomment-59183307</a>
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-1-2" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-1-2"><a href="http://octopress.org/">Octopress</a> with <a href="https://github.com/yoshinari-nomura/org-octopress">org-octopress</a></h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-1-2">
<p>
I also noticed <a href="http://blog.paphus.com/blog/2012/08/01/introducing-octopress-blogging-for-org-mode/">this post</a> and tried it. 
I&#8217;m not sure of pros and cons of each, but I followed upper link because
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>It looks simpler.
</li>
<li>It is in Elpa package list, while the other is not.
</li>
<li>More recent, more users (concerning github stars)
</li>
<li><a href="http://www.railsonmaui.com/blog/2014/03/05/octopress-setup-with-github-and-org-mode-v2/">newer post of this blog</a> suggests to use it, while the <a href="http://www.railsonmaui.com/blog/2013/04/27/octopress-setup-with-github-and-org-mode/">older post of this blog</a> suggests to use the other.
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>




